Reversing previous estimate to pre-January, 70/30 split, given recent jump in cases.
How the holiday interferes with testing seems like the deciding factor here. It looks to me like the average tips over 200k right on New Years day.
Now seems a projected inevitability, but I'd echo @m_collier 's sentiments remembering the human lives and life costs involved in these depressing forecasts.

Another data point way over 200k for the 22nd. Case counts just have to be “flat” from here on out (statistically) to resolve things this week. I’m now pretty sure this will be the week, because Mondays are often anomalously large, but Wednesdays are often typical and not even the second-largest case count in any given week, when there is a growing wave. Would be very happy to be wrong though—obviously, such high case counts represent a lot of additional people who will soon be suffering or even dying.

CDC reported cases: Dec 18: 75,832 Dec 19: 93,431 Dec 20: 288,381 Dec 21: 204,913 Preliminary data not from CDC for Dec 22: 242,794 Current 7 day average using Dec 22 data, from NYT: 171,380 Sum of Dec 18 to 22: 905,351 To reach 200k by Dec 24: need ~495k more => 247k average for Dec 23 and 24. This is possible. Sum of Dec 19 to 22: 829,519 To reach 200k by Dec 25: need ~570k more => 190k average for Dec 23 to 25. Suppose Dec 25 cases are ~175k. Then will need 198k/day on Dec 23 and 24. Considering how massively Omicron already swept through (the less densely populated) Canada, there's probably a freak tide in the U.S. with regards to new confirmed cases and test positivity rates (test positivity in Canada already surpassed 10%).

Last two days cases have been over 200K. Possible slowdown in testing over the holidays. It’s going to be either December or January, and I’m leaning slightly January. South African data shows a quick drop in daily cases following a quick spike, making February or later a likely non-starter as we are about one month behind them.

New cases Dec 22: 243,619; 7-day average: 167,477. The 7-day average rose 6.5%. I do think 200k/day is likely, although possibly not before Dec 25 now. I think it probably won't quite make it to 200k before Christmas. I suspect it will be just under 200k on Dec 24, although 200k could still happen.

For Dec 22, New York state is reporting 28,924 cases, the largest number ever; their 7-day average is going to go up by 11%. Illinois reported 16,681 cases, and their 7-day average is going to go up 9%. If the rest of the US tracks similarly (a big "if"), the new 7-day average for Dec 21 could be ~10% up, or ~173k. If that happens, it's not too much of a stretch to picture >=200k/day on Friday. That would avoid the big holiday dip associated with Christmas as well.
Christmas Eve, Christmas Day, day after Christmas have lower reporting rates – but this does not seem to hold on NYE and NYD.
Worldometer 197k today, and still 13 states without data… seems like 22th will again be >200k.

If you start from the 20th… 20–> 288k, 21–> 204k. 908k left—>need to average 181k on other 5 days. That is not impossible if 2 more days would be arround 200k again. X-mas eve and day could have “off” days with smaller numbers.
I need to see one more data point before pushing bin 2 up further. But there is little doubt we will see the average over 200k over the next few weeks.

I see a lot of people forecasting fairly high probabilities for bin 2 over the past few days, and I wonder to what extent different people are taking into account lower testing/reporting rates that can be expected to occur over the holidays relative to what cases would be otherwise. There's a lot of uncertainty here, imo.
Mostly off the back of Yankee Candle complaint data (1), and ~288k cases on 20 December

Testing capacity over Christmas and new year season is a technical factor that might see this fall (just) into bucket 3, but using the UK's trend graph as an indicator of how steady the growth curve might be (straight as a die and nearly identical with the US since 14 Dec 21) [1] it seems as a projection that the US 7 day average increase sits at 8000 new cases a day over the next couple of weeks (for comparison the last time the US hit 200,000 the daily increase rate was about 6000 cases a day on the up spike).

I had previously lowered my forecast on bin 2 a bit because I expect a severe dip in testing and reporting from Dec 25 to Jan ~4, relative to what cases would have been otherwise. But I also wonder whether some places might expand testing capacity over the holidays because of Omicron. If it weren't for the holidays, there'd be no question in my mind that 200k/day would be reached by the end of the year. So, for now, I'm raising my forecast on bin 2. @Anneinak what do you think?

Only a few days left until December 31st. The testing might have trouble keeping up with the surge in Omicron cases. The holidays will further limit testing. The question is a 7 day average, and so will likely be decided soon, one way or the other.

Big jump in cases today in spite of decrease expected from “holiday reporting issue”. This will apparently be a race between Omicron on one hand and US testing/reporting limits on the other to determine if the 200k mark is exceeded just before or just after New Year’s.
Using London as a demographic pre cursor of speed of spread.
The only reason I am not higher is testing capacity for Christmas and the timing of being. If don't hit Bin2 then it will be the following week I suspect
A jump to 298 (or 270) is a big jump. Watching a few cities the numbers are looking UKish. I will follow daily numbers for a couple of days but I am thinking that we should be hitting bin2 hard soon

I was going to wait for the rest of the week to see what case counts do, but at this point, why not put some probability on an 80k/day increase in the 7-day avg. taking place in just ~ 2 weeks. Just because it’s absolutely bonkers doesn’t mean it’s not happening. With Omicron, the more unlikely it seems, the more likely it is to happen apparently.

The NYT has 270k cases on December 20th (299k minus the 29k Maryland data blip). This is higher than my estimate a few days ago. The surge is accelerating. https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/covid-cases.html

New cases Dec 20: 268,307 excluding MD backlog of 28,541 cases 7 day average: 142,973 (+10,163) https://twitter.com/BNODesk/status/1473106730343145472 Reported cases are going up despite the holidays. That tells you just how much Omicron is spreading. There might just be an upset, and this question might resolve in bin 2. But I do think reported cases will very likely drop after this Friday, so if cases are going to reach 200k, it would need to happen fast.

The 7-day moving average was more than 130k on December 19th. New York City is seeing a dramatic increase in cases. NYC population is 8 million, but the daily confirmed cases will be limited by test capacity. There are reports of long lines in NYC to get tested, with more test sites opening up this week. The CDC wants more data, and is surely watching NYC closely.
Still sitting on the fence on this one a little bit. That reported cases are going up at all right now is a testament to just how much actual cases are going up.

@belikewater has made some points that I consider important. . . -increased use of quick, at-home testing may decrease # of tests taken at test sites and reported to the CDC -a tsunami of new cases may overwhelm test sites & labs, delaying counts -last year there was a significant (approx 18%) slowing/decrease in the # of tests reported during the holiday period, perhaps due to: -short-staffing due to holidays & illness (omicron!) at testing sites & labs may further delay testing -employees of businesses which close for the holidays will not be being tested

Rethinking. We really need to see what happens this week. The highest 7-day average of cases/day for all of December last year was on the Sunday before Christmas, so Dec 19 would likely be the peak this year, too, if it weren't for Omicron, and Dec 31 would be the minimum during the holidays. This week we will start to get an idea of whether Omicron's growth will overcome reduced testing during the holidays and increased use of home tests.

The number of people getting tests sure doesn't seem to be slowing down. Just one example: https://twitter.com/MarkLevineNYC/status/1472576237788880907 And that's an awful lot for a Sunday: "New York reports 22,478 new coronavirus cases, the biggest one-day increase on record, of which 12,404 are in New York City" https://twitter.com/BNODesk/status/1472667941829283847 US Covid cases last Sunday: 35.5k. Today: 64.7k. NY state alone has 22.5k cases. Over 7.6k cases in Ohio.
Cases at 127.7k and trending upwards after a short dip (up from 119k last week).
I think testing and reporting will likely fall too much during the remainder of the year to reach 200k/day by then. Otherwise, I think it would definitely happen before Dec 31.

Daily cases are starting to increase, from 118k to 125k in the last week. New York City and Florida are examples of how quickly cases can double. Maybe above 130k on Dec 19th, and above 200k on Dec 29th.

Some very troubling signs from a highly vaccinated populace. Models show daily new cases likely to surge past last winter’s highs. https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2021/12/18/omicron-variant-denmark/
Cases jumped last week, so 200K this month is possible. Before March seems really likely given Omicron.

Today's number for the 7 day average is 122,296. To have a 7-day average of 200k cases by 12/31, there will have to be an AVERAGE increase in the AVERAGE of 5,5xx per day. Looking at the new cases per day (orange line), there's a significant increase in cases per day which is going to translate into a significant increase in the 7-day average.
Bin 2 seems possible if there is a rise in Omicron cases that is as rapid as in the UK/EU. If not Bin 2 then it's hard to see it going past Bin 3.

Based on last year, we could expect case reports to dip from today through early January from where they would have been without the holidays, with a minimum on Dec 31. However, I suspect that with Omicron exploding, I expect cases to continue to increase at least somewhat through late next week, and I think we may still see a 7-day average of 200k before Dec 31. But it will likely be a nailbiter, and it might resolve to bin 2 only on Dec 31. With Omicron cases exploding, I also think that increasing use of at-home rapid tests will reduce reported cases. Watch and wait.

As I expected would likely happen, the doubling time in at least one community where they are actually collecting a lot of data is ~2.2 days. I suspect that the previously estimated doubling time of 3.7 days resulted from insufficient data. https://twitter.com/trvrb/status/1471651856011051011

The 7-day average is 118,515. This represents an increase of 37.3% over the past week. If this rate of increase continues, in 2 weeks the 7-day average will be 222,441. However, the omicron variant seems to be more contagious than delta, so I'm expecting the increase WoW to exceed 37.3%. BUT, there's the problem that last year there was a period at the holidays in which there was an 18% drop in reported cases; I'm assuming that this was due to short-staffing because of the holidays. That reduces my confidence in an estimate that the 7-day average of cases will exceed 200k by CYE.
This seems worth noting. There's still plenty of uncertainty. https://twitter.com/ScottGottliebMD/status/1471670787853725706?t=YguWuedpoaw4sC2Yyz3v6w&s=19

Cases are rising very fast, so 200K is possible this year, but not likely. But early next year is looking quite likely. Cases have been rising very rapidly. A lot of vulnerable people, and a lot of resistance to masking in many places. Better uptake on vaccines, but they don’t offer instant immunity.

US daily cases remain flat around 120k. New York City is starting to see exponential growth in daily confirmed cases [1]. Less than 20% in the US have taken a booster dose, and a booster is needed to prevent Omicron infection, and so Omicron will spread rapidly, but it will take a few weeks. The previous increase from 120k to 200k took about 4 weeks (November 9 to December 7, 2020). Omicron will spread faster, maybe in 1 to 3 weeks. But it hasn't started yet, except in NYC.
US cases have plateaued, but it feels like the calm before the storm.

1) as pointed out by @borisn , the “effective” doubling rate of Omicron is likely to be slower than the 2-3 day “single-reservoir” doubling rate that is often cited in reference calculations, and that seems to be based primarily on case-rate evolution in South Africa and UK. The main argument I’ve seen for why this would be is related to the spatial and social compartmentalization of the US, and the need for the virus to “jump” into new sub-populations before it can continue to spread. This process would cause some delay in the onset/growth rate of the wave that would make a bin #2 outcome pretty difficult to achieve (only 2 weeks left), given today’s case counts.

New York City is the only large US population I can find that might be seeing exponential growth in daily confirmed cases. US daily cases remain flat around 120k. The highest Nowcast estimate is 13% Omicron share in Region 2. Daily confirmed cases in this region are: New York (excluding NYC): 7k flat New York City: 4k increasing with a 10-day doubling time. New Jersey: 4.5k increasing with a 13-day doubling time.
Today the average is 117,890. So the average would have to increase by 82,111 for this question to close.
I think we would see 200k/day if it weren't for the dip in reporting over the holidays.
Omicron.
My guess: 130k to 200k takes 1 week. Above 130k on December 19th. Above 200k on December 26th. I will update my probabilities when I see more than 130k daily cases (7 day moving average).

If it weren't for the holidays, I'd be 100% on bin 2; I'd expect cases to rise to 300k+/day by the end of the year. If testing/reporting will be effectively capped during the holidays enough to keep the 7-day average below 200k/day, then it'll be bin 3. If testing/reporting are only cut by a *percentage*, say around 20% like last year (18% last year), then it'll be bin 2. I'm not sure which way this is going to go.
Omicron surge plus delta
Currently at 119k and trending upwards (up from 108k last week). Although there seems to be a lull in upward trajectory in the last few days.

I have no idea what will happen next. Prior expectations—supported by the observable evidence reported in all the official channels (CDC)—indicate that Delta on its own will be unlikely to cause another very large wave anytime soon. Omicron, however doesn’t seem to have nearly the volume of officially reported case data that I’d expect to see based on comments in this GJO forum and twitter, but there’s a lot of reasonable arguments for why we should expect a spike soon.
Adjusting December down due to passage of time, and a growth rate that is insufficient to reach 200,00. Adjusting the next bib up for Omicron.

Given how quickly Omicron is spreading in the UK, I suspect the US is not far behind. The US could possibly see 200k cases/day from Delta + Omicron by the end of the year. We simply don't have the surveillance that the UK does, so we're flying relatively blind in comparison. In favor of 200k by the end of the year (bin 2): * Omicron is spreading widely, and Delta + Omicron cases may actually reach >> 200k/day. * Many locations have little to no restrictions in place. * People aren't changing their behaviors much and still don't anticipate the speed of exponential spread. In favor of bin 3 instead: * Testing and reporting go way down during the holidays. Reported cases fell 25% over Thanksgiving, despite actual cases rising. Last year, reported cases fell 18% over Christmas and New Year's, despite actual cases rising. * Perhaps related to the point above, could testing capabilities become saturated in some locations? * Locations could put substantial restrictions in place. * Omicron may not be as widespread as I think it likely is.

7d-average expected to roughly double over the next 20 days, based on Oct/Nov 2020 CDC data. This time around there is a double variant cocktail in the mix with higher transmissibility plus a lower-than-optimal vaccination status for almost half of the US population (however, some protection achieved), thus there's going to be a slight advantage for the pandemic. Based on 2020, at this point in time a steepening of the curve seems likely and this question could possibly resolve on 26 Dec, a few days sooner than 2020 data would otherwise suggest.
Minor shuffle, I feel that I am a bit high on December still so will drop right off in a week

Now I'm starting to wonder whether Delta + Omicron could cause cases to reach 200k by the end of the year. If cases double every 3 days instead of 4 (cases and case percentages do seem to be doubling more rapidly in the UK than in SA), and if Omicron causes 4% of cases now, then it's not inconceivable that Omicron could cause 100k cases/day by the end of the year. BUT, testing and reporting will go way down after Dec. 17, if this year is like last year. So, I'll leave a 5% possibility of bin 2.

See https://outbreak.info/location-reports?loc=USA, which suggests a prevalence of ~2% for Omicron on Dec 2; the doubling time is likely 3 days. If one assumes conservatively that Omicron is causing 3%-4% of cases in the US now, and exponential growth in Omicron cases with a doubling time of 4 days, then the US could see 200k cases/day by mid-January. Hopefully some mitigations, individual behavioral changes and seasonality will slow this down, but I don't see any major barrier to reaching 200k at some point before Feb. 28. I hope I'm wrong.... I'm leaving 15% on the last bin for now in case I am. I think bin 2 is out because, based on last year, cases would have to reach 200k/day by next Friday Dec 17, with likely little change between this Friday and next, and the average is still at ~120k/day.

Thanks to @Maarten for helping me think about bin 2 some more. I was forgetting that Mondays are big reporting days. Taking that into account, I agree with his forecast of 15% on bin 2. And if cases don't reach somewhat close to 200k by Thursday or Friday of this week, I think bin 2 will be out. Update Tuesday evening: 117k cases today, 7-day average 119k. Bin 2 isn't looking likely, but it's not looking impossible yet either.
Actually, Delta cases may not be turning around. I had seen one report that there were 85k cases today, but there were actually ~192k.

Delta cases seem to be turning downward, so that all but rules out bin 2 in my mind. I think bin 3 is extremely likely as Omicron spreads faster than people can imagine. It looks to be almost as contagious as chickenpox. But so many people have already made up their minds that they're not going to take Covid seriously, and I suspect a lot of states/counties/etc. aren't going to put restrictions in place, including some with leaders who would be inclined to do so but won't for political reasons. So, I fear that very little existing immunity + winter + Omicron being just slightly less contagious than chickenpox = huge spread. I fear mitigations won't come until things are way out of control, because that will likely happen very quickly. It is interesting to me that the crowd currently assigns 29% probability to 200k cases being reached between Jan 1 and Feb 28; I don't see how it will be avoided. I assign some non-zero probabilities to the last 2 bins in case I'm wrong.

It doesn't look likely that Delta will get us to 200k by the end of the year, but Omicron is coming after that. I think we will see a very large number of cases in January. I don't think Omicron is going to peak in early January at all. It's too contagious, and the US has little immunity to it.
Currently at 108k, and trending upwards. Thanksgiving may be influencing these numbers, but probably not by too much.
If it's not Delta in bin 2, it'll be Omicron in bin 3. It's starting to look like Delta won't make it to 200k by the end of the year, though.

Cases are rising rapidly, so an increase to 200,000 by the end of the year is now more likely. With omicron, a surge similar to delta is possible. The numbers to watch here are how contagious it turns out to be and vaccine effectiveness.

It is starting to look more likely that in addition to escaping much existing immunity, Omicron may be more transmissible. There's still little evidence that can separate out increased transmissibility vs. increased immune escape, but I found this to be a rather compelling graph that supports the idea that Omicron may actually be more transmissible: https://twitter.com/rid1tweets/status/1466828284445040645 And here's one among several estimates of R0 by highly respected scientists: https://twitter.com/macroliter/status/1466808886342651909

Prior to the new Omicron variant I would have said 1 Jan- 28 Feb would have been low probability (~<10%), but with that uncertainty I feel the need to increase that to closer 25%. Very hard to predict beyond 1 March at this stage but leaning towards better awareness (both govt. and general public) leading to more caution ensuring the number stays below 200k until after 1st May.
139k cases on Dec 3 and increasing. There's a real possibility of reaching a 7-day average of 200k/day by the end of the year.
Significantly increased the modeled transmissibility rate starting 20 days from now. Previously already modeled increased mobility during the Holiday Season.

Based on peak months for upper-respiratory infections (due to lower humidity and increase of in-person gatherings), COVID is likely to peak between December and February (with February being the most likely month, if only based on trends from other upper-respirator viruses). 200,000 cases were reached in December for COVID last year, but this was without an available vaccine and with social distancing measures implemented nation-wide. This will be the first winter season with most restrictions lifted, but with vaccines available. As summer cases were higher in 2021 than summer 2020 (after governments lifted restrictions), COVID is widely in circulation, and more infectious than the flu, I predict reaching 200,000 cases in December for the 7 day moving average is likely. COVID cases may instead peak in historically high months for the flu (February) due to vaccination/booster schedules.

It's not clear to me whether enough of the US has the political will at this point to put enough of a limit on the size of a potential Omicron wave, which would likely explode in late Jan to mid Feb in the absence of mitigation. If 100 cases were present in the US as of 11/27/21 and the doubling time is 5 days (one current estimate is 4.8d), then we could see ~100k cases/day by the end of January. But I don't rule out Delta putting us over 200k cases/day by the end of the year. I also don't think Omicron is the only variant that may spread well in the US. For example, it's possible that Omicron could turn out to escape nearly all neutralizing antibody immunity but be barely more transmissible than the ancestral variant, while some other variant (B.1.1.640? Others?) could turn out to escape some intermediate portion of existing antibody immunity but be more transmissible than Omicron. Which would spread more quickly in the US (and elsewhere), and how much would they spread? And what restrictions would be put in place to limit their spread (probably not much)?

A closer look at the 2020-2021 US holiday wave shows its “compound” nature (three, progressively larger new caseload spikes separated by two significant dips). A commonly encountered interpretation of this observation is that there is 1) a lull in testing / strong incentive to delay seeking medical treatment until directly after the Thanksgiving and Christmas holidays while families are gathered; 2) significantly increased chances for new infections driven by large numbers of people traveling together in confined spaces and gathering indoors for festivities with trusted family members. This explains the apparent dip in cases coinciding with the specific holiday dates and the strong rebound in cases beyond previous highs thereafter.
Must be in winter.Especially in the coldest time.

Rt is about 1.10 by some estimates and still growing, similar to values at the same time last year. (Note that cases peak when Rt falls to 1, so we know that cases have not yet peaked.) https://ourworldindata.org/explorers/coronavirus-data-explorer?time=2020-04-10..latest&facet=none&Metric=Reproduction+rate&Interval=7-day+rolling+average&Relative+to+Population=true&Align+outbreaks=false&country=~USA Based on last year, I think we can expect a dip in reported cases from Wed through the following week, compared to what they would be without the holiday, followed by a resumption of the increasing trend. With 158k cases reported today, I think it's possible that we could see a 7-day average of 200k in the coming weeks. Or there could be a lower peak, most likely in January.
Cases are rising again, and recent trends in Europe may show up here in the coming months. There is evidence of a seasonal effect in the case rate, which is additional evidence for an increase.

Unfortunately, this seems like a more real possibility than it did one month ago. I still doubt that bucket 4 has much of a chance because of more people spending time outside again as spring comes. My guess is it most likely won't get to 200,000 by the time this question finishes, but I think there is a relatively high chance it gets to at least 150,000.

I'm starting to think that some of the immunity in the US has acquired so far by infection and/or vaccination may be overcome by Delta's transmissibility and by time (leading to waning immunity). I had thought that the Delta wave would likely wrap up in Dec, perhaps after a small, gentle rise in cases around now, but looking at Europe and at the steepness of the current rise of cases in the US, I'm beginning to think that might be wrong. Delta is still very much making its way through the US population, and almost no mitigations are in place. Also, there's B.1.640 to worry about.
With the recent sudden increase in Europe and USA, I have adjusted my forecast to reflect the possibility that we could see a 7 day average above 200k before the end of this year.

I'm wondering whether vaccinations might be outweighed by Delta's increased infectivity and waning immunity to the extent that we could see a fairly large spike this winter. Especially if Delta Plus or some other variant becomes a bigger problem.

Adjust for passage of time. As cases are starting to tick up in the Northern most states, and as we also see an uptick in Europe, I think it is increasingly likely that we will see a repeat of last year's numbers.

Given rates of vaccination, booster, reduced tests ans natural immunity I don’t think it is as likely to get a big peak again as far as 200k a week. In addition different parts of the country are now in independent cycles and one part of the country will have a wave when another one eases off. So the different rates in different states balances off. All states would need a surge at the same time as happened before. If people travel over Christmas there is a possibility in January of higher rates, but the travel is the cause. So I think this level of infection is unlikely to happen again, but still giving it a reasonable probability before May anyway.

CDC reports cases detected. Last time cases exploded, there was not a day over 200 000. If severity rises again, it will increase hospital use, and decrease cases reported by CDC. The only things that could change that would either be a massive rise in testing, a decrease in vaccine efficacy, or a decrease in severity. A decrease in severity would increase actual case count, but would also reduce detection. Unless the disease gets back into the population that actually gets tested, it's not going to happen. (And cases are about to drop a bunch as people <12 get the vaccine.) Waves take too long to happen in November, and require synchronization.
Unreported cases will rise significantly as a mix% because the severe cases will continue weakening substantially.
Either we will have turned the corner or we won't have.

Adjust for passage of time. Cases today are very similar to Nov 2 last year (74k 11/2/21 vs 89k 11/2/2020). With the recent uptick, I see the trend following last year's trend, peaking in January 2022.
The data is starting to suggest we are entering an upswing. Adjusting accordingly.

The last few days of data suggest that we may be nearing the bottom of this wave. Adjusting accordingly. Although my intuition is that increased resistance will reduce transmission below the target, that's not necessarily the case.
Apparently I’m on the completely opposite end of the “thought-spectrum” on this Question, compared to @belikewater : I’m fighting an urge to put too much weight in bins 2-4!

I really think there's no chance of this happening before May 1, 2022, but I continue to try to force myself to assign some probability to categories that just don't seem possible or very likely, too. Data Observations: - In ~1.5 years, the US apparently experienced three "simple" new infection peaks (none of which exceeded even 100k/day) and two "compound" new infection peaks that are larger and have internal sub-peaks/troughs. At least one of the compound peaks exceeded 200k/day (Nov20-Jan21 peak; we are currently in the midst of the second "compound" peak, TBD if it will exceed 200k/day) - By eyeball, during approximately half of the time interval since the first COVID outbreak, there was no active new infection peak (steady or falling baseline), and the longest between-peak time interval was roughly 4 months. The two "compound" peaks observed so far are 6-7 months apart. - The current new infection rate during the ongoing "compound peak" (Sep21) is now at ~150k/day, although this value has been stagnant for a while now. The previous compound peak achieved ~150k/day, and rapidly progressed to exceed 200k/day, whereas the current compound peak seems significantly "flatter" at present. - During the period of COVID, only the Delta variant emergence seems to significantly have changed the evolution of COVID in the US (beyond the initial COVID strain to hit the US population).
It is tempting to be optimistic as we see cases level off or drop but a look at last winter and spring does not give me enough confidence to go in strongly for "not before 1 May 2022".

Rethinking. It would take a strain to infect ~15% or 16% of the US population to get to average daily totals >200k. Not even Delta is likely to infect that many. With Delta sweeping through now and largely wrapping up around December, and so many vaccinated, resulting in maybe >95% of the population with some immunity, it's hard to picture a wave that big happening so soon on the heels of Delta, or perhaps ever, depending on what variants emerge and how many people keep up with vaccinations.

Last year, the 7-day moving average of daily cases did not spike to >200k until Dec. 6, and it remained barely >200k from Dec. 6 to 24, when there was far less widespread immunity. Moreover, Delta is making its way through the population at the moment, and will likely cause a much smaller peak of cases this winter as population immunity reaches levels >90%. In addition, one or more new variants capable of taking Delta's place have not clearly emerged. In short, I don't see a strong case for >200k in bin 2, but it's possible. If one or more new variants emerge, perhaps even sublineages of Delta, then bins 2 or 3 could be possible, although a variant that substantially escapes existing immunity would be required imo. We're in uncharted territory here. Will cases start to settle down once nearly everyone in the US has some form of immunity? As for bin 1, I don't think we'll see >200k before Nov. 1 because I think the Delta wave will generally be winding downwards between now and Oct. 31 (with perhaps an additional, lower peak between now and then). I think bin 4 would require a variant with extreme immune escape.
